  "relevant_summary": "Observed benefits reported include: increased species richness of plants and bumblebees; higher species richness and/or abundance of spiders; higher abundance of ground-dwelling invertebrates and ground beetles; increased stone curlew breeding population size; higher northern lapwing hatching success; higher Eurasian skylark nesting success; establishment, abundance or species richness of rare arable plants; and breeding by lapwing, skylark, grey partridge and yellow wagtail on lapwing plots [562]. Studies also report increased Eurasian thick-knee numbers following schemes promoting plots; multiple species associated with and using lapwing plots for foraging or nesting; and higher nesting success in fallow fields or lapwing plots than in crops in two of three studies [213]. For butterflies and moths, some studies found higher abundance of butterflies and micro\u2011moths on farms with agri\u2011environment schemes including these margins, higher butterfly abundance and richness in fields with wider margins in one of two years, and higher abundance of some butterflies under enhanced agri\u2011environment options, though other butterflies were lower [3923]. Reported drawbacks or neutral findings include: no effect on 11 of 12 farmland bird species or on ground beetles in some studies; fewer seed\u2011eating birds on fallow plots in two of three regions; more pernicious weeds on uncropped cultivated margins than on conservation or conventional headlands; and a lower proportion of young grey partridges where such margins/plots were common [562]. Additional neutral or negative findings include: no effect on grey partridge density changes; 11 species not associated with plots and fewer birds using plots than cropland in two of three regions; grey partridge productivity not related to the amount of lapwing plots and a lower proportion of young partridges on sites with many cultivated fallow plots [213]. For butterflies and moths, several studies reported similar species richness or abundance on farms or fields with these options compared to controls, indicating mixed responses [3923].",
